{{Spanish name|Calzada|Terrados}} {{Infobox Officeholder | name = Blas Calzada Terrados | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | office = President of [[Comisión Nacional del Mercado de Valores]] | term_start = 22 September 2001 | term_end = 6 October 2004 |predecessor = Pilar Valiente Calvo |successor =Manuel Conthe Gutiérrez |office2 = Chairman of [[Instituto Nacional de Estadística (Spain)|Instituto Nacional de Estadística]] |term_start2 = 1977 |term_end2 = 1979 |predecessor2=Andrés Fernández Díaz |successor2=José Montes Fernández | birth_date = {{birth date|1937|06|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Valladolid]], [[Spain]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2018|2|17|1937|06|8|df=y}} | death_place = [[Madrid]], Spain | residence = | nationality = Spanish | occupation = Economist | party = |alma_mater= [[University of Valladolid]] | spouse = | children = | website = | box_width = }} '''Blas Calzada Terrados''' (8 June 1937 – 17 February 2018), was a [[Spain|Spanish]] economist.
He studied at the Zorrilla Institute of [[Valladolid]], graduated in Economics and began studying Political Science at the [[University of Valladolid]]. He studied two years in [[Paris]]: Marxist economics and in the second year ''Planning Techniques'' and ''National Accounting''. Through a grant from the French Ministry of Finance Calzada worked in the Center of Assistance to Foreign Officials (ASTEF).
He was hired by the [[Instituto Nacional de Estadística (Spain)|National Institute of Statistics (INE)]] to draft the Technical Report of Revenue. He later approved the exams for the newly created Research Service of the [[Bank of Spain]] where he stayed for three years, after which he worked for seven years as an advisor and executive in different companies, mainly in the food sector. He was one of the founders of the economy magazine ''Cambio 16''.
He was Director General of the INE between 1977 and 1979, period in which he participated in the drafting of the economic plan of the ''Moncloa Pacts''. After this period he was hired by the Trade Union Board of the [[Bolsa de Madrid]] as Director of the Economic Studies Service and was subsequently appointed Chairman of the [[Comisión Nacional del Mercado de Valores|National Securities Market Commission (CNMV)]] between 22 September 2001 and 6 October 2004.<ref>[http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-21-09-2001/abc/Economia/blas-calzada-sustituira-a-pilar-valiente-al-frente-de-lanbsp;cnmv_48299.html Blas Calzada sustituirá a Pilar Valiente al frente de la CNMV] {{es icon}}</ref>
Later he held the chairmanship of the Technical Advisory Committee of the [[IBEX 35]] (CAT) <ref>[http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias-gaceta/politica/ley-estabilidad-presupuestaria Ley de Estabilidad Presupuestaria] {{es icon}}</ref>and president of the La Salle Innovation Park.
