{{Other uses|Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja}}
'''Dukljan''' or '''Dukljanin''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Дукљан}} or {{lang|sr|Дукљанин}}) is a figure in [[Serbian mythology]]<ref name=SMR>{{cite book |author=Š. Kulišić |author2=P. Ž. Petrović |author3=N. Pantelić |script-title=sr:Српски митолошки речник |year=1970 |publisher=[[Nolit]] |location=Belgrade |language=Serbian |pages=111–112 |chapter=Дукљан(ин) }}</ref> that is a [[reflection (mythology)|reflection]] of the [[Roman emperor]] [[Diocletian]].<ref name=SMR/> He is presented as the [[devil|adversary]] of [[God]],<ref name=SMR/> possibly because of the real [[Diocletianic Persecution|Diocletian's persecution of Christians]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rastko.org.rs/rastko/delo/11001 |title=О називу Диоклeје пре Немањића |author=[[Đorđe Janković]] |accessdate=2008-08-16 |date=2007-09-06 }}</ref>
Legends attribute to him building of the town of [[Duklja (town)|Duklja]],<ref name=SMR/> [[Dukljan's border]],<ref name=SMR/> and the [[Roman road#Milestones|Roman milestones]] near [[Tuzi]] (according to a folktale, he was throwing them at his brother and sister as they were fleeing to [[Zahumlje|Hum]]).<ref name=SMR/>
A Serbian folk song about Dukljan says that he once removed the [[The Sun in human culture|Sun]] from the sky and brought it to the Earth.<ref name=SMR/> [[John the Baptist|Saint John]] managed to trick him and restore the Sun, but afterwards, while chasing him, Dukljan grabbed at him and tore a piece of flesh from John's foot, which explains why humans have [[arches of the foot]].<ref name=SMR/>
Several variants of a story that he is still alive exist; according to them he is chained in the [[Morača]] river near [[Duklja (town)|Duklja]] (the [[Vizier's bridge]]).<ref name=SMR/> In some of them, he constantly gnaws at his chains, and each year around [[Christmas]] (or around [[Đurđevdan]]) nearly manages to break free and destroy the world, when four [[Romani people|Gypsy]] [[blacksmith]]s reforge the chains.<ref name=SMR/>
==See also== {{wikisource|Tsar Dukljan}} * [[Kjárr]]
==References== <references/>
{{Slavic mythology}}
