The '''International Entente Against the Third International''' ({{lang-fr|Entente internationale contre la III:e internationale}}, after 1938 the '''International Anticommunist Entente''', {{lang-fr|Entente Internationale Anticommuniste EIA}}) was an international [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] organisation based in [[Geneva]], [[Switzerland]].
The organisation was founded by the Swiss advocate [[Théodore Aubert]] and Russian émigré Red Cross leader Georges Lodygensky as a response to the [[Communist International]] in 1924.<ref name ="New Perspective">{{cite book |last1=Durham |first1=Martin |last2=Power | first2=Margaret |date=2010 |title=New Perspectives on the Transnational Right |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q_hjDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26 |location=Google Books |publisher=Palgrave McMillan |pages=26–31 |isbn=0230115527 |access-date=3 February 2017 }}</ref> Its objectives were to defend the "principles of order, family, property and nationality".<ref name ="New Perspective" />
The entente had national chapters in over 20 countries, with the aim of influencing political and journalistic circles.<ref>{{cite book |last=Courtois |first=Stéphane |date= 2007 |title=Dictionnaire du communisme |url= |location= |publisher= |page=93 |isbn=978-2035837820 |language=French}}</ref> The British chapter was the Central Council of the [[Economic League (United Kingdom)|Economic League]]s.<ref name ="New Perspective" /> In Finland, the national chapter ''Suomen Suojelusliitto'' was founded by the prominent statesman [[Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim]] a year earlier in 1923 to do anti-communist education.<ref>[http://runeberg.org/pieni/4/0246.html Pieni Tietosanakirja IV. San Remo - Öölanti]. Otava 1928.</ref> According to some accounts, [[Francisco Franco]]'s anti-communism was initially sparked by reading the entente's publications and he also met Aubert.<ref name ="New Perspective" /> Other notable sympathizers included [[Philippe Pétain]] and [[Franz von Papen]].<ref name ="New Perspective" />
EIA published ''Revue Anticommuniste''.<ref name="LasserreStuder1996">{{cite book|author1=André Lasserre|author2=Brigitte Studer|title=Sous l'œil de Moscou: le Parti communiste suisse et l'Internationale, 1931-1943|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0v5DAQAAIAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Chronos-Verlag|isbn=978-3-905311-56-3|page=771}}</ref> EIA opened an information centre in August 1937.<ref name="LasserreStuder1996"/>
After [[World War II]], EIA's membership numbers greatly decreased and its leaders considered the [[United States]] to be a better center for leading anti-communist activities than Europe.<ref name ="New Perspective" /> The organisation ceased operation in 1950.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1980 |title=Guide to the Hoover Institution Archives |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-7JxqQ8qRWUC&pg=PA141&lpg=PA141&dq=%22International+Anticommunist+Entente%22+1950&source=bl&ots=ge2mzOd09_&sig=UEPM4oNExctbB5LL_5-bavQP5tw&hl=fi&sa=X&ei=Nq2YVYKHB8GYsAHPmK6ADQ&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22International%20Anticommunist%20Entente%22%201950&f=false |location=Google Books |publisher=Hoover Press |page=141 |isbn= |access-date=5 July 2015 }}</ref>
