{{Infobox government agency | agency_name = Latvian Police | type = Law enforcement agency | nativename = Latvijas Valsts policija | logo = | logo_width = | logo_caption = | seal = | seal_width = | seal_caption = | picture = | picture_width = | picture_caption = | formed = {{Start date|1918|12|5|df=y}} | preceding1 = | dissolved = | superseding = | jurisdiction = [[Government of Latvia]] | headquarters = Čiekurkalna 1.līnija 1 k- 4, [[Rīga]] | coordinates = | motto = | employees = | budget = | chief1_name = [[General]] Ints Ķuzis<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vp.gov.lv/?id=406&said=406&rsd=1|title=About us > Chief of the State police|last=|first=|date=|website=www.vp.gov.lv|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> | chief1_position = Chief of the State Police | chief2_name = | chief2_position = | chief3_name = | chief3_position = | chief4_name = | chief4_position = | chief5_name = | chief5_position = | agency_type = | chief6_name = | chief6_position = | chief7_name = | chief7_position = | chief8_name = | chief8_position = | chief9_name = | chief9_position = | parent_department = | parent_agency = [[Ministry of the Interior (Latvia)|Ministry of the Interior]] | child1_agency = | child2_agency = | keydocument1 = | website = {{URL|http://www.vp.gov.lv}} | footnotes = }}
The '''State Police of Latvia''' (also '''Latvian State Police''', {{lang-lv|Latvijas Valsts policija}}) is the national [[law enforcement agency]] of [[Latvia]]. It is subordinate to the [[List of Ministers of the Interior of Latvia|Ministry of the Interior]]. The agency is divided into five Regional Administrations ([[Riga]], [[Courland|Kurzeme]], [[Latgale]], [[Vidzeme]], [[Zemgale]]), which are responsible for policing priorities and the availability of public security police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vp.gov.lv/?id=71&said=71&rsd=1|title=About us > The State Police of Latvia|last=|first=|date=|website=www.vp.gov.lv|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>
== History == The founding date of the Latvian Police is considered to be 5 December 1918, when the transitional government of the newly-proclaimed Republic of Latvia, the [[People's Council of Latvia]], approved the Temporary Regulations on the Internal Security Organization ([[Latvian language|Latvian]]: ''Pagaidu noteikumi par iekšējās apsardzības organizēšanu''), which regulated the structure of the police force and put it under jurisdiction of the [[Ministry of the Interior (Latvia)|Ministry of the Interior of Latvia]], led by [[Miķelis Valters]]. The date is now commemorated in Latvia as the Day of the Police. The regulations ordered the formation of 23 police districts - one for each district of Latvia and 6 prefectures of the largest cities (Riga, [[Liepāja]], [[Daugavpils]], [[Jelgava]], [[Rēzekne]], [[Ventspils]]).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Latvijas policijas vēsture, 2. sējums; 7. sējums|last=Žīgure|first=Anna|publisher=Fakts|year=1998|isbn=9789984925103|location=|pages=}}</ref>
Due to the ongoing [[Latvian War of Independence]] and the lack of territory controlled by Latvian forces at that time, the force could only begin its activities in the summer of 1919 after the [[Latvian National Armed Forces|Latvian Army]] and its allies had liberated large parts of the country from the [[Red Army]]. Facing a lack of qualified personnel, the Police School at the Riga Prefecture was opened in the same year.
After the war, the force was further divided into the Civil (''Kārtības policija''), Criminal (''Kriminālpolicija'') and Secret Police (Political Police, ''Politiskā policija''). The Latvian Criminal Police became a member of [[Interpol]] in 1929.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iem.gov.lv/eng/ministry/history/|title=History - Ministry of the Interior|last=|first=|date=|website=www.iem.gov.lv|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> After the [[Soviet occupation of Latvia in 1940|Soviet occupation of Latvia]] in 1940, the police force was dissolved and former servicemen persecuted under the Soviet regime. Law enforcement in the [[Latvian Soviet Socialist Republic|Latvian SSR]] was primarily the task of the Soviet [[militsiya]].
After the [[On the Restoration of Independence of the Republic of Latvia|restoration of the independence of Latvia]], the Latvian Police was re-established in 1991, with one of the first units being the 1st Police (Patrol) Battalion on 30 April 1991. The main task of the battalion, which was the first armed formations of the Latvian government, was to provide security of the [[Supreme Council of the Republic of Latvia|Supreme Council of Latvia]] and strategically important buildings (government offices, [[Latvijas Radio|radio]] and [[Latvian Television|television]]). In 1992, the battalion was renamed as the [[Latvian Security Service of Parliament and State President|Security Service of the Republic of Latvia]], which was merged into the [[Latvian Military Police|Military Police]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bataljons.lv/index.php/vesture.html|title=1. Policijas bataljons - Vēsture (1st Police Batallion - History)|last=|first=|date=|website=bataljons.lv|language=lv-lv|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref> Latvia rejoined Interpol in 1992.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interpol.int/Member-countries/Europe/Latvia|title=Latvia / Europe / Member countries / Internet / Home - INTERPOL|website=www.interpol.int|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-21}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Law enforcement in Latvia]] * [[State Border Guard]] * [[Latvian Military Police]]
